a, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (widespread, especially in the southeast): from the genitive singular or nominative plural form of Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ).","Irish: when not of English origin, this may be a variant of   Healy   or   McHale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a (usually remote) nook or corner of land, from Old English and Middle English <i>hale</i>, dative of <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, or a habitational name from a place so named such as Hale in Cheshire, Hampshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Holme Hale (Norfolk), Hale Street (Kent), and Haile (Cumberland). In northern England the word often has a specialized meaning, denoting a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend. See   Haugh  . In southeastern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."]},{"name":"Hayles","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hales  .","variant of   Ayles   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hailes","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Hailes in Colinton (Midlothian), originally in East Lothian, named from the Middle English genitive or plural form of <i>hall</i> ‘hall’.","English: variant of   Hales   (see also   Hayles  )."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Ralph De Hales was born about 1248, in Hales, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Baron Walter Hale, was 47 and his mother, Berenguer Eleanor, was 32. He married Denenta Le Clauer in 1273, in Harwich, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1313, in Harwich, Essex, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"Abt 1248–1313":"umbes 1248–1313","1248–1313":